1
00:00:00,543 --> 00:00:02,377
<i>[CLOCK TICKING]</i>

2
00:00:05,214 --> 00:00:06,881
[#]

3
00:00:21,263 --> 00:00:22,897
<i>[MAN PANTING]</i>

4
00:01:00,002 --> 00:01:01,836
<i>[MAN PANTING]</i>

5
00:01:35,071 --> 00:01:39,007
<i>MAN: Sometimes I admit to
myself that it's possible</i>

6
00:01:39,008 --> 00:01:41,943
<i>I will never be able
to finish my life's work.</i>

7
00:01:46,082 --> 00:01:47,983
<i>My one and only book.</i>

8
00:01:50,353 --> 00:01:53,355
<i>And that in the end,
without her...</i>

9
00:01:56,726 --> 00:01:58,360
[#]

10
00:01:59,829 --> 00:02:02,631
<i>...there will be nothing.</i>

11
00:02:02,632 --> 00:02:04,366
<i>And I will die alone.</i>

12
00:02:07,903 --> 00:02:09,838
[CRYING]

13
00:02:21,450 --> 00:02:23,051
<i>What are you doing here,
Coane Dominic?</i>

14
00:02:26,088 --> 00:02:28,890
I have a migraine.

15
00:02:28,891 --> 00:02:30,525
I thought a walk might help.

16
00:02:30,526 --> 00:02:33,295
But in your pajamas
on Christmas Eve?

17
00:02:33,296 --> 00:02:34,863
Don't catch cold. Look.

18
00:02:37,600 --> 00:02:40,035
At the first opportunity,
I'll...

19
00:02:42,872 --> 00:02:45,040
What do you do
at the first opportunity?

20
00:02:47,276 --> 00:02:50,545
DOMINIC: At the first
opportunity, I have to-- I have--

21
00:02:50,546 --> 00:02:52,380
It's in the drawer.

22
00:02:52,381 --> 00:02:55,417
I-- I have saved--
I saved it for--

23
00:02:55,418 --> 00:02:59,321
At the first opportunity,
I will open the blue envelope.

24
00:03:01,090 --> 00:03:04,993
Not here in Piatra Neamt
where everyone knows me,

25
00:03:04,994 --> 00:03:06,161
but somewhere far away.

26
00:03:10,900 --> 00:03:13,001
Bucharest perhaps.

27
00:03:13,002 --> 00:03:14,069
At Easter.

28
00:03:16,572 --> 00:03:18,506
[#]

29
00:04:24,974 --> 00:04:25,974
[BELL TOLLING]

30
00:04:25,975 --> 00:04:27,876
[HORN HONKING]

31
00:04:29,679 --> 00:04:30,645
[THUNDER CRASHES]

32
00:04:39,956 --> 00:04:41,256
<i>Universul.</i>

33
00:04:42,591 --> 00:04:44,059
<i>Universul.</i>

34
00:04:52,802 --> 00:04:58,273
<i>BOY: Special Easter
edition. Universul.</i>

35
00:04:58,274 --> 00:05:00,909
War clouds over Romania.

36
00:05:00,910 --> 00:05:02,077
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

37
00:05:02,078 --> 00:05:03,411
WOMAN:
Oh, it's pouring.

38
00:05:15,591 --> 00:05:17,592
<i>Universul.</i>

39
00:05:30,573 --> 00:05:32,307
WOMAN: He was struck by lightning.

40
00:05:32,308 --> 00:05:33,375
WOMAN 2:
Call an ambulance.

41
00:05:35,177 --> 00:05:38,046
WOMAN 3:
Call for some help.

42
00:05:38,047 --> 00:05:40,582
WOMAN 4: Look, who knows
what sins he has committed

43
00:05:40,583 --> 00:05:42,284
that God would strike him
on Easter.

44
00:05:42,285 --> 00:05:47,722
They say whoever dies during
Easter goes straight to heaven.

45
00:05:50,726 --> 00:05:52,727
[#]

46
00:05:54,730 --> 00:05:56,231
<i>WOMAN:
Dominic.</i>

47
00:06:02,405 --> 00:06:04,773
DOMINIC:
Oh...

48
00:06:04,774 --> 00:06:08,209
<i>I will wish you.
You know what I mean. I mean...</i>

49
00:06:10,112 --> 00:06:13,214
<i>I will love you
until the day I die.</i>

50
00:06:24,560 --> 00:06:28,463
MAN:
The eye seems intact,

51
00:06:28,464 --> 00:06:32,734
but I don't know
if he is blind or not.

52
00:06:32,735 --> 00:06:35,437
I don't even know
if he's conscious,

53
00:06:35,438 --> 00:06:41,576
if he hears or
if he understands what he hears.

54
00:06:41,577 --> 00:06:47,015
If you understand what I say,
squeeze my finger.

55
00:06:59,528 --> 00:07:02,030
I'm Dr. Roman Stanciulescu.

56
00:07:02,031 --> 00:07:04,466
I'm here to help you.

57
00:07:07,570 --> 00:07:09,170
Good.

58
00:07:09,171 --> 00:07:11,606
We wish to find out
your age.

59
00:07:11,607 --> 00:07:15,877
For every 10 years,
squeeze my finger once.

60
00:07:20,483 --> 00:07:21,283
Ten.

61
00:07:24,387 --> 00:07:26,187
Twenty.
Twenty.

62
00:07:27,723 --> 00:07:28,957
Thirty.

63
00:07:31,794 --> 00:07:33,261
Forty.
Forty.

64
00:07:34,830 --> 00:07:36,031
Fifty.
Fifty.

65
00:07:37,967 --> 00:07:39,768
Sixty.
Sixty.

66
00:07:42,505 --> 00:07:44,773
Seventy.
WOMAN: Seventy.

67
00:07:46,642 --> 00:07:47,842
Seventy years old.

68
00:07:49,545 --> 00:07:53,548
MAN: Seventy. I would
have thought less.

69
00:07:53,549 --> 00:07:58,320
Well, in this larval state,

70
00:07:58,321 --> 00:08:00,121
it's hard to estimate.

71
00:08:06,095 --> 00:08:07,629
[#]

72
00:08:15,705 --> 00:08:18,306
<i>WOMAN: I've never
met anyone like you.</i>

73
00:08:18,307 --> 00:08:21,743
<i>You want to know
absolutely everything.</i>

74
00:08:21,744 --> 00:08:24,245
Laura, try to imagine

75
00:08:24,246 --> 00:08:27,048
conceiving a passion
for something,

76
00:08:27,049 --> 00:08:29,517
having one desire,
dedicating your life to it

77
00:08:29,518 --> 00:08:31,186
and then failing.

78
00:08:31,187 --> 00:08:32,354
I am 26.

79
00:08:32,355 --> 00:08:34,089
I have no accomplishments,

80
00:08:34,090 --> 00:08:36,391
I've made no discoveries.

81
00:08:36,392 --> 00:08:37,993
I'm a failure.

82
00:08:37,994 --> 00:08:39,928
ROMAN:
Do you have a wife?

83
00:08:41,430 --> 00:08:42,931
MAN: No.
WOMAN: - No.

84
00:08:42,932 --> 00:08:44,466
MAN:
Nephew?

85
00:08:47,470 --> 00:08:49,471
Yes.
- Nephew.

86
00:08:49,472 --> 00:08:50,872
Nephew.
- Do you want us

87
00:08:50,873 --> 00:08:53,842
to inform your nephew
about your condition?

88
00:08:53,843 --> 00:08:55,944
No.

89
00:08:55,945 --> 00:09:00,115
Let us know the first letter
of your name. Continue.

90
00:09:00,116 --> 00:09:02,450
I am going to say
the alphabet.

91
00:09:02,451 --> 00:09:09,024
A, B, C, D...

92
00:09:09,025 --> 00:09:10,792
D.
- D.

93
00:09:10,793 --> 00:09:14,729
He doesn't live
in Bucharest.

94
00:09:14,730 --> 00:09:18,900
He has only one relative,
a distant one,

95
00:09:18,901 --> 00:09:21,670
and he has no wife.

96
00:09:21,671 --> 00:09:22,837
Thank you.

97
00:09:26,375 --> 00:09:30,045
He'll accept any test,

98
00:09:30,046 --> 00:09:33,181
no matter how dangerous
or painful,

99
00:09:33,182 --> 00:09:36,851
to verify whether
the optic nerve was damaged.

100
00:09:40,056 --> 00:09:41,356
That's interesting.

101
00:09:42,224 --> 00:09:44,159
[#]

102
00:09:52,635 --> 00:09:54,736
[GIGGLING]

103
00:09:54,737 --> 00:09:56,871
How old did you say he was?

104
00:09:56,872 --> 00:09:58,273
Seventy.

105
00:09:58,274 --> 00:10:00,041
He's hiding his age.

106
00:10:00,042 --> 00:10:03,011
He's a young man
in the prime of his life.

107
00:10:07,650 --> 00:10:10,485
MAN:
I didn't come here...

108
00:10:10,486 --> 00:10:13,154
I came here for an education.
MAN 2: - Come.

109
00:10:13,155 --> 00:10:15,357
What did you think
about the lecture?

110
00:10:15,358 --> 00:10:17,225
MAN: Professor Matei
is getting senile.

111
00:10:17,226 --> 00:10:19,995
He told us the same thing
three or four times.

112
00:10:19,996 --> 00:10:22,397
MAN 2: I didn't
notice. I was asleep.

113
00:10:22,398 --> 00:10:24,199
Let's go get
something to eat.

114
00:10:27,336 --> 00:10:28,870
<i>DOMINIC:
Is it true?</i>

115
00:10:32,208 --> 00:10:34,976
<i>LAURA:
Failure, success.</i>

116
00:10:34,977 --> 00:10:36,978
<i>Such extremes, Dominic.</i>

117
00:10:36,979 --> 00:10:39,414
You yourself taught me
about Chandrakirti.

118
00:10:39,415 --> 00:10:42,884
The concept of tetralemma logic,
the four possibilities.

119
00:10:42,885 --> 00:10:46,187
What you say is so,
or it is not so,

120
00:10:46,188 --> 00:10:48,790
it's also so
and not so combined, heh,

121
00:10:48,791 --> 00:10:51,559
or it's neither so
nor not so combined.

122
00:10:51,560 --> 00:10:53,028
<i>[GASPS] DOMINIC: You know,</i>

123
00:10:53,029 --> 00:10:54,329
<i>I've never told you this,</i>

124
00:10:54,330 --> 00:10:56,631
<i>but Dr. Chavannes' lecture
in Paris...</i>

125
00:10:56,632 --> 00:10:57,799
I waited to see him.

126
00:10:57,800 --> 00:11:01,937
I was hoping that he would
accept me as a student.

127
00:11:01,938 --> 00:11:06,107
And he told me that if I didn't
master Chinese, Sanskrit,

128
00:11:06,108 --> 00:11:09,878
Tibetan and Japanese,

129
00:11:09,879 --> 00:11:12,781
I would never become
a great Orientalist.

130
00:11:12,782 --> 00:11:14,015
But didn't you tell him

131
00:11:14,016 --> 00:11:16,051
you wanted to study
only the Chinese language?

132
00:11:16,052 --> 00:11:17,385
I did.

133
00:11:17,386 --> 00:11:19,754
<i>I told him that
I'd been studying Chinese</i>

134
00:11:19,755 --> 00:11:21,222
<i>for six months,
six hours a day.</i>

135
00:11:21,223 --> 00:11:23,024
<i>He stepped up
to the blackboard.</i>

136
00:11:23,025 --> 00:11:25,660
<i>He wrote
some 20 characters on it,</i>

137
00:11:25,661 --> 00:11:27,062
<i>and he asked me
to pronounce them</i>

138
00:11:27,063 --> 00:11:30,165
<i>one by one
and then translate the passage.</i>

139
00:11:30,166 --> 00:11:33,034
<i>In order to master Chinese,</i>

140
00:11:33,035 --> 00:11:36,171
<i>one must have
the memory of Mandarin.</i>

141
00:11:36,172 --> 00:11:40,275
<i>Photographic memory.</i>

142
00:11:40,276 --> 00:11:42,243
<i>A memory of a Mandarin.</i>

143
00:11:43,546 --> 00:11:45,347
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

144
00:11:45,348 --> 00:11:48,249
MAN: I remember hearing
about another case,

145
00:11:48,250 --> 00:11:50,418
a priest hit by lightning.

146
00:11:50,419 --> 00:11:52,354
Burned over his whole body

147
00:11:52,355 --> 00:11:54,823
and would survive
many years afterwards.

148
00:11:54,824 --> 00:11:57,058
True, he was left
blind and mute,

149
00:11:57,059 --> 00:11:58,960
as our man is also probably.

150
00:11:58,961 --> 00:12:02,631
Don't talk so loud.
Maybe he can hear you.

151
00:12:02,632 --> 00:12:04,633
I want him to hear me.

152
00:12:04,634 --> 00:12:08,069
Let's see how he'll react.
Maybe he isn't mute at all.

153
00:12:08,070 --> 00:12:09,771
No!
[YELPS]

154
00:12:09,772 --> 00:12:15,076
Not mute! Not mute!

155
00:12:15,077 --> 00:12:17,646
Try to pronounce any word,
anything.

156
00:12:20,816 --> 00:12:25,920
Blue envelope.

157
00:12:25,921 --> 00:12:28,156
WOMAN:
Blue envelope.

158
00:12:28,157 --> 00:12:29,357
Envelope...

159
00:12:29,358 --> 00:12:31,926
[GROANING]

160
00:12:31,927 --> 00:12:34,162
MAN: The teeth,
they're barely holding.

161
00:12:34,163 --> 00:12:36,831
Call the dentist right now
and see if the x-rays are ready.

162
00:12:45,308 --> 00:12:46,508
What's next?

163
00:12:46,509 --> 00:12:49,244
"Romania may be forced
to negotiate with Hitler."

164
00:12:49,245 --> 00:12:52,080
France is abandoning us
to the Nazis.

165
00:12:52,081 --> 00:12:54,382
He is right.

166
00:12:54,383 --> 00:12:55,951
His x-rays have come in.

167
00:12:55,952 --> 00:12:57,919
You really should
take a look at them.

168
00:12:57,920 --> 00:13:03,391
The roots are healthy, but they
are being pushed up by new ones.

169
00:13:07,330 --> 00:13:09,864
So we feel you're out
of danger.

170
00:13:12,501 --> 00:13:15,170
Only now do you begin
to become an interesting case.

171
00:13:15,171 --> 00:13:17,572
You understand why,
don't you?

172
00:13:17,573 --> 00:13:19,407
The way the lightning
struck you,

173
00:13:19,408 --> 00:13:21,743
you had to have been killed
on the spot,

174
00:13:21,744 --> 00:13:25,747
or else to have died
of asphyxiation.

175
00:13:25,748 --> 00:13:29,284
At best you'd
be left paralyzed,

176
00:13:31,754 --> 00:13:34,122
mute or blind.

177
00:13:38,160 --> 00:13:41,896
You are lucky,
I'll give you that.

178
00:13:44,767 --> 00:13:46,234
Yes.

179
00:13:46,235 --> 00:13:49,571
We had ordered a set of dentures
to allow you to eat

180
00:13:49,572 --> 00:13:53,174
and above all,
to speak normally.

181
00:13:53,175 --> 00:13:56,444
But the x-rays show
that, uh,

182
00:13:56,445 --> 00:14:01,816
a new set of teeth
are ready to appear.

183
00:14:01,817 --> 00:14:03,918
It's impossible.

184
00:14:03,919 --> 00:14:06,988
Yes. It's simply impossible.

185
00:14:08,724 --> 00:14:11,493
And yet the x-rays are clear.

186
00:14:13,529 --> 00:14:15,196
You are getting new teeth.

187
00:14:17,266 --> 00:14:20,702
This is no longer a case
of a living dead man,

188
00:14:20,703 --> 00:14:22,504
but of something else.

189
00:14:22,505 --> 00:14:25,874
What, exactly,

190
00:14:25,875 --> 00:14:27,709
we still don't know.

191
00:14:27,710 --> 00:14:31,146
Your recovery is amazing.

192
00:14:32,748 --> 00:14:35,583
[MOANING]

193
00:14:35,584 --> 00:14:37,786
I don't want to tire you out.

194
00:14:37,787 --> 00:14:40,188
Get some rest.
I'll be back tomorrow.

195
00:14:44,327 --> 00:14:47,028
[BELLS TOLLING]

196
00:14:47,029 --> 00:14:49,631
News stories
and feature articles

197
00:14:49,632 --> 00:14:52,667
are starting to appear
in different papers,

198
00:14:52,668 --> 00:14:55,837
the majority of them absurd,
ridiculous.

199
00:14:59,175 --> 00:15:00,809
What are you doing?

200
00:15:10,620 --> 00:15:12,020
New teeth!

201
00:15:13,856 --> 00:15:18,693
But you must help us
understand this.

202
00:15:18,694 --> 00:15:21,896
We have to know more about you,
who you are,

203
00:15:21,897 --> 00:15:23,198
what your profession is.

204
00:15:23,199 --> 00:15:25,934
What's your real age?

205
00:15:25,935 --> 00:15:28,637
Please cooperate
a little more.

206
00:15:31,040 --> 00:15:33,508
Were you so stubborn
when you were young?

207
00:15:36,479 --> 00:15:38,246
Always.

208
00:15:38,247 --> 00:15:41,016
<i>MAN: What is this you
insist on writing, young man?</i>

209
00:15:41,017 --> 00:15:45,987
Well, I've almost finished
with antiquity, the Middle Ages.

210
00:15:45,988 --> 00:15:50,325
But the most exciting part,
the origins.

211
00:15:50,326 --> 00:15:52,294
The origins of language, of--

212
00:15:52,295 --> 00:15:54,195
But when will
you finish it, Dominic?

213
00:15:54,196 --> 00:15:56,698
He needs 10 lifetimes
to do it all.

214
00:15:56,699 --> 00:15:59,534
DOMINIC: The origins of
language, human consciousness,

215
00:15:59,535 --> 00:16:01,403
even the idea
of time itself.

216
00:16:01,404 --> 00:16:04,205
This would call for years
of research.

217
00:16:04,206 --> 00:16:06,775
And what with the inexperience
of our provincial...

218
00:16:06,776 --> 00:16:08,910
[BELLS TOLLING]
...librarians.

219
00:16:08,911 --> 00:16:11,379
I'm terribly sorry,
professor.

220
00:16:13,015 --> 00:16:17,285
I have an appointment.
I really must run.

221
00:16:17,286 --> 00:16:19,554
[#]

222
00:16:19,555 --> 00:16:23,258
He's brilliant. Brilliant. But--

223
00:16:25,328 --> 00:16:29,464
Laura, I'm so sorry.
I completely forgot.

224
00:16:29,465 --> 00:16:31,166
We have to talk,
Dominic.

225
00:16:31,167 --> 00:16:32,801
It's very important
for both of us,

226
00:16:32,802 --> 00:16:35,003
and I can't hide it
any longer.

227
00:16:35,004 --> 00:16:36,705
Of course.

228
00:16:36,706 --> 00:16:39,207
It's snowing. Should we go
to the Café Select?

229
00:16:39,208 --> 00:16:43,645
No. And please don't interrupt.
It's not what you think.

230
00:16:53,556 --> 00:16:56,992
I feel that you aren't mine,

231
00:16:56,993 --> 00:16:59,227
that you are never here with me.

232
00:16:59,228 --> 00:17:02,464
That you--
That you live in another time.

233
00:17:04,934 --> 00:17:06,801
I'm not thinking
of your research,

234
00:17:06,802 --> 00:17:09,671
which in spite of what
you believe, does interest me.

235
00:17:09,672 --> 00:17:11,840
I wanted to help you
with that.

236
00:17:11,841 --> 00:17:15,110
But you keep yourself shut away
in an alien world,

237
00:17:15,111 --> 00:17:16,544
one I can't enter.

238
00:17:18,881 --> 00:17:21,683
So for my sake and for yours,

239
00:17:21,684 --> 00:17:24,619
we should break
our engagement and separate.

240
00:17:24,620 --> 00:17:26,187
No.

241
00:17:26,188 --> 00:17:27,255
Laura, no.

242
00:17:27,256 --> 00:17:30,025
We are still young.

243
00:17:30,026 --> 00:17:32,193
We both love life.

244
00:17:35,431 --> 00:17:37,999
You will have more time
for your research.

245
00:17:40,369 --> 00:17:41,303
You'll see later.

246
00:17:43,406 --> 00:17:45,340
[#]

247
00:18:10,700 --> 00:18:12,667
[GROANING]

248
00:18:16,973 --> 00:18:18,406
Tell the professor
what he wants to know.

249
00:18:20,710 --> 00:18:22,877
Tell him you need
a new identity.

250
00:18:30,886 --> 00:18:33,588
All right, you can go.
I'll be here all afternoon.

251
00:18:43,132 --> 00:18:45,133
I understand
that you are willing

252
00:18:45,134 --> 00:18:47,068
to speak to me candidly.

253
00:18:49,805 --> 00:18:52,107
You don't have to make
a great effort.

254
00:18:52,108 --> 00:18:55,477
The words you cannot pronounce,
you can write.

255
00:19:02,251 --> 00:19:03,451
My name...

