00:41:31,133 --> 00:41:34,569
in order to create
the necessary confusion.

518
00:41:36,439 --> 00:41:38,974
The double.

519
00:41:38,975 --> 00:41:42,510
He always answers the questions
I'm ready to ask.

520
00:41:42,511 --> 00:41:44,312
Like a true
guardian angel.

521
00:41:44,313 --> 00:41:48,650
Now that's a correct
and useful formula.

522
00:41:48,651 --> 00:41:50,318
Are there others?

523
00:41:50,319 --> 00:41:51,920
Many.

524
00:41:51,921 --> 00:41:53,855
For example?

525
00:41:53,856 --> 00:41:58,960
Along with angels and guardian
angels, there are powers:

526
00:41:58,961 --> 00:42:01,029
Archangels,

527
00:42:01,030 --> 00:42:03,999
seraphim, cherubim.

528
00:42:04,000 --> 00:42:07,869
Intermediary beings
par excellence.

529
00:42:07,870 --> 00:42:09,671
Intermediary
between consciousness

530
00:42:09,672 --> 00:42:12,607
and unconsciousness?

531
00:42:12,608 --> 00:42:14,075
Well, of course.

532
00:42:15,544 --> 00:42:18,246
But also between
nature and man,

533
00:42:18,247 --> 00:42:21,149
man and the divine,

534
00:42:21,150 --> 00:42:25,220
reason and Eros.

535
00:42:25,221 --> 00:42:27,856
Feminine and masculine,

536
00:42:27,857 --> 00:42:30,025
darkness and light,

537
00:42:30,026 --> 00:42:31,893
matter and spirit.

538
00:42:31,894 --> 00:42:33,461
[SIGHS]

539
00:42:35,064 --> 00:42:37,966
So it's come back
to my old passion again:

540
00:42:39,435 --> 00:42:42,771
philosophy of religion.

541
00:42:42,772 --> 00:42:45,373
Yes,

542
00:42:45,374 --> 00:42:47,809
for you it will always
come back to that.

543
00:42:50,413 --> 00:42:52,914
But I can't believe
in the objective reality

544
00:42:52,915 --> 00:42:55,850
of the person
with whom I'm conversing. I--

545
00:42:57,286 --> 00:43:01,056
I can only think of him
as my double.

546
00:43:01,057 --> 00:43:03,758
Well, in a sense,

547
00:43:03,759 --> 00:43:06,027
that's what he is, but...

548
00:43:07,763 --> 00:43:11,633
that doesn't mean
he doesn't exist

549
00:43:11,634 --> 00:43:14,336
in an objective way
independently.

550
00:43:14,337 --> 00:43:16,371
Oh, I'd like to be convinced,
but--

551
00:43:16,372 --> 00:43:21,309
In metaphysical controversies,
empirical proofs

552
00:43:21,310 --> 00:43:23,845
lose their value, but...

553
00:43:28,451 --> 00:43:31,720
wouldn't you enjoy receiving

554
00:43:31,721 --> 00:43:34,889
a few fresh roses

555
00:43:34,890 --> 00:43:36,691
picked from the garden?

556
00:43:36,692 --> 00:43:38,994
I've always liked roses.

557
00:43:38,995 --> 00:43:41,329
Well, where would you like me
to put them?

558
00:43:43,332 --> 00:43:46,301
Not in the vase,
at any rate.

559
00:43:48,738 --> 00:43:51,840
One right here

560
00:43:51,841 --> 00:43:53,375
in my hand...

561
00:43:55,611 --> 00:43:59,114
as I'm holding it now, open.

562
00:43:59,115 --> 00:44:00,882
[#]

563
00:44:08,691 --> 00:44:10,759
And another on my knee?

564
00:44:17,366 --> 00:44:19,267
The third rose.

565
00:44:19,268 --> 00:44:21,970
Where do you want me
to put the third rose?

566
00:44:23,539 --> 00:44:25,307
Let's see.

567
00:44:28,711 --> 00:44:31,947
Things are more serious
than we thought.

568
00:44:31,948 --> 00:44:36,451
We know now why the Gestapo
will try anything,

569
00:44:36,452 --> 00:44:38,820
anything, in order to get
their hands on you.

570
00:44:40,923 --> 00:44:42,090
Why?

571
00:44:42,091 --> 00:44:45,493
Among the intimates
of Goebbels,

572
00:44:45,494 --> 00:44:48,530
there is an enigmatic
and ambiguous person,

573
00:44:48,531 --> 00:44:51,533
a certain Dr. Josef Rudolf.

574
00:44:51,534 --> 00:44:54,135
[CAMERA CLICKS]

575
00:44:54,136 --> 00:44:55,804
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

576
00:44:55,805 --> 00:44:59,407
<i>Dr. Rudolf believes that
electrocution by a current</i>

577
00:44:59,408 --> 00:45:01,409
<i>of at least a million volts</i>

578
00:45:01,410 --> 00:45:03,745
<i>could produce
a radical mutation</i>

579
00:45:03,746 --> 00:45:05,714
<i>of the human species.</i>

580
00:45:08,851 --> 00:45:10,251
<i>Word of these experiments</i>

581
00:45:10,252 --> 00:45:13,254
<i>has reached the ear
of Adolf Hitler,</i>

582
00:45:13,255 --> 00:45:16,925
<i>who has become personally
interested in your case.</i>

583
00:45:16,926 --> 00:45:18,927
[MEN SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

584
00:45:18,928 --> 00:45:22,430
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]

585
00:45:22,431 --> 00:45:25,200
[IN GERMAN] Attention!
The experiment begins!

586
00:45:27,336 --> 00:45:29,271
[MEN SHOUTING]

587
00:45:48,424 --> 00:45:52,927
[IN ENGLISH] They want
us to lend you to them

588
00:45:52,928 --> 00:45:55,497
for a period of time.

589
00:45:55,498 --> 00:45:57,966
God help me.

590
00:45:57,967 --> 00:45:58,867
Time, Dominic,

591
00:46:00,436 --> 00:46:03,505
we are running out of time.

592
00:46:03,506 --> 00:46:05,941
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

593
00:46:05,942 --> 00:46:07,842
[MAN SPEAKING IN GERMAN
OVER PA]

594
00:46:13,582 --> 00:46:16,251
MAN [IN GERMAN]: Austrian-Swiss
border. Passport control.

595
00:46:16,252 --> 00:46:20,221
Please disembark
with all luggage.

596
00:46:28,164 --> 00:46:31,900
[MAN SPEAKING IN GERMAN
OVER PA]

597
00:46:34,570 --> 00:46:35,637
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

598
00:46:35,638 --> 00:46:36,538
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

599
00:46:45,348 --> 00:46:47,182
[TRAIN CHUGGING]
[BELL DINGING]

600
00:46:52,655 --> 00:46:57,125
[MAN SPEAKING IN GERMAN
OVER PA]

601
00:47:04,133 --> 00:47:06,901
An order has just come in
from Vienna

602
00:47:06,902 --> 00:47:11,406
that certain nationals
will be detained.

603
00:47:11,407 --> 00:47:14,809
But why? I have
a valid passport and visa.

604
00:47:14,810 --> 00:47:16,278
Please take a step back.

605
00:47:22,718 --> 00:47:24,286
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

606
00:47:28,157 --> 00:47:30,091
[CHATTERING IN GERMAN]

607
00:47:43,272 --> 00:47:45,473
Go on!

608
00:47:45,474 --> 00:47:49,411
My cooperation with the Nazis
is only symbolic.

609
00:47:49,412 --> 00:47:50,078
Go ahead.

610
00:47:52,348 --> 00:47:53,548
DOMINIC:
Thank you.

611
00:47:53,549 --> 00:47:55,216
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

612
00:47:55,217 --> 00:47:57,018
[#]

613
00:48:26,916 --> 00:48:28,149
<i>DOMINIC [IN ENGLISH]:
Geneva.</i>

614
00:48:28,150 --> 00:48:31,453
<i>1941, May the 7th.</i>

615
00:48:31,454 --> 00:48:34,255
<i>Dominic Matei, dictation.</i>

616
00:48:41,530 --> 00:48:44,366
The documents in the Geneva
safety-deposit box

617
00:48:44,367 --> 00:48:47,669
summarize my life,
which was profoundly changed

618
00:48:47,670 --> 00:48:49,738
in the spring of 1938,

619
00:48:49,739 --> 00:48:52,007
in front of the Gara de Nord
railway station

620
00:48:52,008 --> 00:48:53,341
in Bucharest.

621
00:48:53,342 --> 00:48:54,843
My first experiences

622
00:48:54,844 --> 00:48:58,747
were described and analyzed
by Professor Roman Stanciulescu,

623
00:48:58,748 --> 00:49:02,550
in reports which were
confiscated by the Nazis.

624
00:49:02,551 --> 00:49:05,453
[WHIRRING]

625
00:49:05,454 --> 00:49:07,455
<i>[#]</i>

626
00:49:07,456 --> 00:49:09,991
<i>DOMINIC:
The war rages around me.</i>

627
00:49:09,992 --> 00:49:12,794
<i>I am a fugitive
in neutral Switzerland,</i>

628
00:49:12,795 --> 00:49:14,262
<i>encircled by the Axis powers.</i>

629
00:49:20,202 --> 00:49:23,571
<i>My Romanian homeland has
made a pact with the devil,</i>

630
00:49:23,572 --> 00:49:25,407
<i>Adolf Hitler,</i>

631
00:49:25,408 --> 00:49:27,876
<i>and may soon be under siege.</i>

632
00:49:29,245 --> 00:49:31,746
<i>[GUNSHOT]</i>

633
00:49:31,747 --> 00:49:33,682
<i>I've lost contact
with my dear friend,</i>

634
00:49:33,683 --> 00:49:35,317
<i>Professor Stanciulescu,</i>

635
00:49:35,318 --> 00:49:36,551
<i>which could mean
that he's been killed.</i>

636
00:49:39,922 --> 00:49:41,723
[CAMERA CLICKING]

637
00:49:46,729 --> 00:49:48,229
<i>I live in fear,</i>

638
00:49:48,230 --> 00:49:50,765
<i>dreading what awaits
in the alleyways.</i>

639
00:49:50,766 --> 00:49:53,001
<i>Eluding capture by my wits,</i>

640
00:49:53,002 --> 00:49:55,537
<i>moving from hotel
to rooming house,</i>

641
00:49:55,538 --> 00:49:57,472
<i>always working on my book.</i>

642
00:49:58,574 --> 00:50:00,241
<i>[GUNSHOT]</i>

643
00:50:00,242 --> 00:50:02,777
<i>November the 30th, 1941.</i>

644
00:50:02,778 --> 00:50:07,515
<i>Zurich. Dominic Matei.</i>

645
00:50:07,516 --> 00:50:09,084
<i>I have explained
in portfolio B</i>

646
00:50:09,085 --> 00:50:11,052
<i>how I instinctually
found the talent</i>

647
00:50:11,053 --> 00:50:13,755
<i>to preserve myself.</i>

648
00:50:13,756 --> 00:50:15,724
<i>Living like a secret agent,</i>

649
00:50:15,725 --> 00:50:19,160
<i>I discovered abilities
to forge documents,</i>

650
00:50:19,161 --> 00:50:21,963
<i>change addresses
and prepare disguises.</i>

651
00:50:21,964 --> 00:50:23,164
<i>[GUNSHOT]</i>

652
00:50:28,604 --> 00:50:32,040
<i>Shortly before he disappeared,
Professor Stanciulescu</i>

653
00:50:32,041 --> 00:50:34,809
<i>arranged a bank account
for me in Geneva</i>

654
00:50:34,810 --> 00:50:36,745
<i>under the name
of William Pedersen.</i>

655
00:50:38,481 --> 00:50:41,016
<i>Now, without him,
these funds will be depleted.</i>

656
00:50:41,017 --> 00:50:43,285
Oh, good morning,
Mr. Pedersen.

657
00:50:43,286 --> 00:50:45,987
<i>And I will have
to find other means.</i>

658
00:50:45,988 --> 00:50:46,955
<i>[GUNSHOT]</i>

659
00:50:48,391 --> 00:50:51,826
<i>February the 20th, 1942.</i>

660
00:50:51,827 --> 00:50:53,662
<i>Bern.</i>

661
00:50:53,663 --> 00:50:57,599
<i>I must face the undeniable
and chilling truth,</i>

662
00:50:57,600 --> 00:50:59,134
<i>that I am a mutant.</i>

663
00:50:59,135 --> 00:51:02,570
<i>Like a character
in a science-fiction novel,</i>

664
00:51:02,571 --> 00:51:05,874
<i>I am a strange superman
of the future.</i>

665
00:51:07,610 --> 00:51:12,480
<i>I have access to knowledge
unavailable to mankind.</i>

666
00:51:12,481 --> 00:51:15,450
<i>Powers I don't fully
understand.</i>

667
00:51:17,820 --> 00:51:20,422
<i>[GUNSHOT]</i>

668
00:51:20,423 --> 00:51:24,693
<i>Despite this, I try to behave
as an ordinary intellectual,</i>

669
00:51:24,694 --> 00:51:26,895
<i>working to complete my book,</i>

670
00:51:26,896 --> 00:51:29,097
<i>documenting the origin
of language</i>

671
00:51:29,098 --> 00:51:31,266
<i>and human consciousness.</i>

672
00:51:31,267 --> 00:51:35,303
<i>I began to realize that
with any text I had before me,</i>

673
00:51:35,304 --> 00:51:37,472
<i>if I wanted to know
the content,</i>

674
00:51:37,473 --> 00:51:40,976
<i>I simply...knew it.</i>

675
00:51:43,346 --> 00:51:45,847
<i>[GUNSHOT]</i>

676
00:51:45,848 --> 00:51:49,551
<i>Lake Campione.
October the 23rd, 1942.</i>

677
00:51:53,556 --> 00:51:56,891
<i>I found I could augment
my income.</i>

678
00:51:56,892 --> 00:52:00,428
<i>Winning just enough
not to arouse suspicion.</i>

679
00:52:00,429 --> 00:52:03,098
No more bets.

680
00:52:03,099 --> 00:52:06,668
<i>Nothing is as it seems,
I am the proof of that.</i>

681
00:52:06,669 --> 00:52:08,203
We've got a winner.

682
00:52:08,204 --> 00:52:09,738
MAN:
Dominic Matei?

683
00:52:09,739 --> 00:52:12,107
Dominic Matei.

684
00:52:12,108 --> 00:52:14,542
<i>I trust no one.</i>

685
00:52:16,012 --> 00:52:17,579
Look at these.

686
00:52:17,580 --> 00:52:19,848
See? These were taken
at the clinic

687
00:52:19,849 --> 00:52:22,717
of Dr. Stanciulescu...

688
00:52:22,718 --> 00:52:26,021
in 1938.

689
00:52:26,022 --> 00:52:30,091
And to think, 10 months ago,
on January 8th,

690
00:52:30,092 --> 00:52:31,459
you turned 74 years old.

691
00:52:33,596 --> 00:52:34,696
CROUPIER:
Eleven again.

692
00:52:34,697 --> 00:52:36,097
You're trying
to look older too.

693
00:52:36,098 --> 00:52:38,066
Those glasses aren't
even prescription.

694
00:52:41,237 --> 00:52:44,606
I still don't-- Thank you.
I still don't know

695
00:52:44,607 --> 00:52:46,508
with whom I have the pleasure
to be speaking.

696
00:52:46,509 --> 00:52:48,643
Ted Jones, Jr.

697
00:52:48,644 --> 00:52:51,713
<i>I'm a correspondent
for LIFE magazine.</i>

698
00:52:51,714 --> 00:52:53,949
Listen.

699
00:52:53,950 --> 00:52:56,985
Switzerland is entirely
surrounded by the Axis powers.

700
00:52:56,986 --> 00:53:00,055
I'm cashing out.
Thank you.

701
00:53:00,056 --> 00:53:02,490
I'm on special assignment
for the United States.

702
00:53:02,491 --> 00:53:05,493
I really think you're
confusing me with someone else.

703
00:53:05,494 --> 00:53:08,229
We can protect your identity,
completely.

704
00:53:08,230 --> 00:53:11,032
I have a very powerful
organization behind me.

705
00:53:11,033 --> 00:53:14,202
I know I can be
of some service to you.

706
00:53:14,203 --> 00:53:16,371
We can pay you, or we can make

707
00:53:16,372 --> 00:53:18,640
some arrangements for you,
anything that might help you.

708
00:53:26,415 --> 00:53:27,983
You know,
your English is perfect,

709
00:53:27,984 --> 00:53:30,251
but you're not saying anything.

710
00:53:34,323 --> 00:53:36,691
I'm afraid I must remain
neutral in all of this.

711
00:53:36,692 --> 00:53:38,059
Now, if you'll excuse me.

712
00:53:39,729 --> 00:53:42,530
<i>If someone were to tell me
that there exist among us</i>

713
00:53:42,531 --> 00:53:47,369
<i>authentic magicians, saints,
bodhisattvas,</i>

714
00:53:47,370 --> 00:53:50,572
<i>or anyone endowed
with miraculous powers,</i>

715
00:53:50,573 --> 00:53:52,040
<i>I would believe them.</i>

716
00:53:52,041 --> 00:53:55,910
In a certain sense,
what you say is true.

717
00:53:55,911 --> 00:53:57,979
But you've attained
the freedom to accept

718
00:53:57,980 --> 00:53:59,447
or reject
these new conditions

719
00:53:59,448 --> 00:54:04,286
to use them to finish
your life's work, or not.

720
00:54:04,287 --> 00:54:06,421
Have you decided?

721
00:54:08,391 --> 00:54:11,326
To use them for good

722
00:54:11,327 --> 00:54:12,894
or for evil.

723
00:54:12,895 --> 00:54:15,363
<i>Have you decided?</i>

724
00:54:31,447 --> 00:54:33,848
[PLAYING CLASSICAL MUSIC]

725
00:54:33,849 --> 00:54:35,784
[CHATTERING
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

726
00:54:35,785 --> 00:54:37,218
<i>Despite my precautions,</i>

727
00:54:37,219 --> 00:54:39,020
<i>I was afraid
I would inadvertently</i>

728
00:54:39,021 --> 00:54:41,856
<i>give myself away
conversing with professors</i>

729
00:54:41,857 --> 00:54:44,025
<i>and colleagues
at the university.</i>

730
00:54:44,026 --> 00:54:47,329
<i>I knew more than any of them
and understood things</i>

731
00:54:47,330 --> 00:54:49,497
<i>they never even
suspected existed.</i>

732
00:55:05,781 --> 00:55:07,148
I know you're
a good friend

733
00:55:07,149 --> 00:55:09,084
of the Romanian
Professor Stanciulescu.

734
00:55:09,085 --> 00:55:13,722
I'm very sorry. I heard he died
in a plane crash, an accident.

735
00:55:13,723 --> 00:55:17,659
But we can talk about this
when my friend gets here.

736
00:55:17,660 --> 00:55:19,628
I told him to come at 9:00.

737
00:55:19,629 --> 00:55:21,563
Your friend?

738
00:55:21,564 --> 00:55:23,999
Dr. Monroe.

739
00:55:24,000 --> 00:55:27,135
The director of an important
gerontology foundation.

740
00:55:28,971 --> 00:55:32,641
He's Swiss, like me.

741
00:55:35,578 --> 00:55:37,112
[WHISPERING]
Like you.

742
00:55:43,819 --> 00:55:45,587
You know,
I do have a name.

743
00:55:46,789 --> 00:55:49,157
Would you like to know it?

744
00:56:00,369 --> 00:56:01,336
Be careful.

745
00:56:04,840 --> 00:56:06,808
He knows who you are.

746
00:56:06,809 --> 00:56:10,445
Hello, I'm Dr. Monroe.

747
00:56:10,446 --> 00:56:12,113
Head of the foundation
investigating

748
00:56:12,114 --> 00:56:13,615
the materials
of Professor Stanciulescu.

749
00:56:17,286 --> 00:56:19,988
I'm afraid I have no idea
to what you're referring.

750
00:56:19,989 --> 00:56:22,357
The belief that youth and life

751
00:56:22,358 --> 00:56:24,526
can be prolonged in any way
other than by the purely

752
00:56:24,527 --> 00:56:25,860
biochemical ones.

753
00:56:25,861 --> 00:56:26,828
You do know
what I'm referring to?

754
00:56:28,864 --> 00:56:30,198
No, I'm sorry.

755
00:56:30,199 --> 00:56:33,234
Methods proposed
by that Nazi, Dr. Rudolf.

756
00:56:33,235 --> 00:56:38,607
Electrocution by means
of a million or more volts.

757
00:56:38,608 --> 00:56:40,141
Insane.

758
00:56:40,142 --> 00:56:43,378
Fortunately, I believe
that method was never tried.

759
00:56:43,379 --> 00:56:46,281
But our informants said
that Professor Stanciulescu

760
00:56:46,282 --> 00:56:49,618
had worked with a somewhat
analogous case of rejuvenation

761
00:56:49,619 --> 00:56:51,519
induced by a bolt
of lightning.

762
00:56:54,991 --> 00:56:57,692
We know who you are,
Mr. Dominic Matei.

763
00:56:59,528 --> 00:57:02,397
Now, I have a prior engagement,
I really must run.

764
00:57:02,398 --> 00:57:04,532
I'm terribly sorry.
- I know.

765
00:57:04,533 --> 00:57:07,535
Perhaps we could have dinner.
Later tonight?

766
00:57:07,536 --> 00:57:09,237
[#]

767
00:57:28,691 --> 00:57:31,326
MONROE:
Mr. Matei?

768
00:57:31,327 --> 00:57:33,395
What do we do with time?

769
00:57:37,633 --> 00:57:39,935
That question,
"what do we do with time"

770
00:57:39,936 --> 00:57:45,607
expresses the supreme ambiguity
of the human condition.

771
00:57:45,608 --> 00:57:48,443
I have no idea
what you're talking about.

772
00:57:48,444 --> 00:57:51,413
An opportunity has been
given to us.

773
00:57:53,316 --> 00:57:55,317
We, the human race.

774
00:57:57,053 --> 00:57:58,253
"We"?

775
00:58:00,356 --> 00:58:01,122
No.

776
00:58:11,968 --> 00:58:15,070
You and I both know
what is coming:

777
00:58:15,071 --> 00:58:17,806
atomic warfare,
cataclysmic destruction.

778
00:58:17,807 --> 00:58:20,008
But unlike the others,

779
00:58:20,009 --> 00:58:24,479
I'm trying to find a meaning
to this impending catastrophe.

780
00:58:24,480 --> 00:58:26,681
Think of me as the last
European optimist.

781
00:58:26,682 --> 00:58:29,284
This can be our life's work.

782
00:58:29,285 --> 00:58:30,785
Please.

783
00:58:34,423 --> 00:58:38,293
There are a few of us who since
1938 have known that you exist.

784
00:58:40,396 --> 00:58:42,497
The fact that you appeared
all of a sudden

785
00:58:42,498 --> 00:58:44,699
means that you have
a special mission

786
00:58:44,700 --> 00:58:48,003
and that you possess means
of knowledge much superior

787
00:58:48,004 --> 00:58:49,904
to those available to us.

788
00:58:49,905 --> 00:58:51,273
You are gravely mistaken.

789
00:58:54,243 --> 00:58:58,380
What is indispensable
to a truly human existence?

790
00:58:58,381 --> 00:59:00,282
For instance,

791
00:59:00,283 --> 00:59:06,021
the Occidental artistic
treasury, music and poetry,

792
00:59:06,022 --> 00:59:09,291
but also a part
of classic philosophy,

793
00:59:09,292 --> 00:59:14,162
and above all, science.

794
00:59:14,163 --> 00:59:16,164
Post-historic man
will be allergic to science

795
00:59:16,165 --> 00:59:17,766
for at least
one or two centuries.

796
00:59:17,767 --> 00:59:22,003
No, always science.

797
00:59:22,004 --> 00:59:24,706
Science above all.
WOMAN: Dominic.

798
00:59:24,707 --> 00:59:26,241
I'm surprised at you.

799
00:59:26,242 --> 00:59:28,643
Dominic, don't believe
anything he says.

800
00:59:28,644 --> 00:59:29,644
[IN GERMAN]
Shut up!

801
00:59:29,645 --> 00:59:31,780
I will tell him the truth.

802
00:59:31,781 --> 00:59:34,115
[IN ENGLISH] Come, Dominic,
join me in this work.

803
00:59:34,116 --> 00:59:35,917
He is Dr. Josef Rudolf,

804
00:59:35,918 --> 00:59:37,886
Hitler's most
dedicated scientist.

805
00:59:40,289 --> 00:59:41,823
Adolf Hitler?

806
00:59:45,695 --> 00:59:47,796
If you actually knew him...

807
00:59:49,598 --> 00:59:52,334
If you had ever been with him,
in his presence...

808
00:59:54,070 --> 00:59:55,804
If I could describe it to you...

809
00:59:57,773 --> 01:00:00,075
Well, uh,

810
01:00:00,076 --> 01:00:01,409
you will meet him soon enough.

811
01:00:07,817 --> 01:00:09,884
No! The Gestapo
had Stanciulescu killed

812
01:00:09,885 --> 01:00:11,152
and Rudolf was the one--
Traitor!

813
01:00:12,455 --> 01:00:13,855
[RUDOLF SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

814
01:00:13,856 --> 01:00:15,824
[BIRDS SQUAWKING]

815
01:00:15,825 --> 01:00:18,326
You have no choice
in the matter.

816
01:00:18,327 --> 01:00:19,861
WOMAN:
Dominic.

817
01:00:19,862 --> 01:00:25,166
[IN GERMAN] You were
the honey in my dreams.

818
01:00:25,167 --> 01:00:27,802
WOMAN [IN ENGLISH]:
Forgive me. Please, forgive me.

819
01:00:27,803 --> 01:00:28,803
[WOMAN SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

820
01:00:31,741 --> 01:00:34,309
It's true what he says.

821
01:00:35,945 --> 01:00:37,746
You really have no choice
in the matter.

822
01:00:43,052 --> 01:00:44,319
[PANTING]

823
01:00:59,735 --> 01:01:01,770
[RUDOLF GRUNTING]

824
01:01:17,687 --> 01:01:18,520
[RUDOLF YELLS]

825
01:01:18,521 --> 01:01:20,488
[GUNSHOT]

826
01:01:20,489 --> 01:01:21,623
[BODY COLLAPSES]

827
01:01:27,663 --> 01:01:30,465
[#]

828
01:01:30,466 --> 01:01:31,833
<i>[GUNSHOT]</i>

829
01:01:32,835 --> 01:01:33,702
<i>[GUNSHOT]</i>

830
01:01:35,137 --> 01:01:35,804
<i>[GUNSHOT]</i>

831
01:01:38,274 --> 01:01:39,374
<i>[BOMB WHISTLING]</i>

832
01:01:39,375 --> 01:01:41,977
<i>[GUNSHOTS]</i>

833
01:01:41,978 --> 01:01:42,978
<i>[BOMB WHISTLING]</i>

834
01:01:42,979 --> 01:01:45,113
<i>[GUNSHOTS]</i>

835
01:01:47,717 --> 01:01:48,783
<i>[BOMB WHISTLING]</i>

836
01:01:52,521 --> 01:01:56,992
DOMINIC:
Geneva 1955, 20th of August,

837
01:01:56,993 --> 01:01:59,494
about 10:31 a.m.
Dominic Matei.

838
01:01:59,495 --> 01:02:03,398
<i>I've decided to stop
making notes in English</i>

839
01:02:03,399 --> 01:02:05,533
<i>and instead to use
an artificial language</i>

840
01:02:05,534 --> 01:02:07,269
<i>of my own invention.</i>

841
01:02:07,270 --> 01:02:11,906
[IN NEW LANGUAGE] Now I can
describe paradoxical situations

842
01:02:11,907 --> 01:02:15,610
impossible to express
in any existing language.

843
01:02:15,611 --> 01:02:17,879
This will permit me
to reveal facts

844
01:02:17,880 --> 01:02:21,316
I have not dared
to confess in writing.

845
01:02:21,317 --> 01:02:23,818
This language will
only be deciphered

846
01:02:23,819 --> 01:02:27,122
by means
of a perfected computer.

847
01:02:27,123 --> 01:02:30,525
So my testimony is addressed
to the future,

848
01:02:30,526 --> 01:02:33,528
let us say in the year 2010.

849
01:02:33,529 --> 01:02:35,330
But to whom?

850
01:02:35,331 --> 01:02:37,899
The coming nuclear wars

851
01:02:37,900 --> 01:02:40,602
will destroy many civilizations.

852
01:02:40,603 --> 01:02:43,838
Undoubtedly, this will unleash

853
01:02:43,839 --> 01:02:49,678
a wave of deep pessimism,
historically unprecedented.

854
01:02:49,679 --> 01:02:52,480
A general despondency.

855
01:02:52,481 --> 01:02:55,817
My testimony,
deciphered in the future,

856
01:02:55,818 --> 01:02:58,620
could counter the despair

857
01:02:58,621 --> 01:03:01,456
because it shows
the potential of humanity:

1
01:03:01,617 --> 01:03:03,551
<i>a species superior</i>
<i>to Homo sapiens,</i>

2
01:03:03,552 --> 01:03:07,188
<i>born in a far-off future.</i>

3
01:03:07,189 --> 01:03:09,958
<i>This depends</i>
<i>on the preservation</i>

4
01:03:09,959 --> 01:03:13,394
<i>of the material</i>
<i>in the safe-deposit box.</i>

5
01:03:13,395 --> 01:03:17,132
<i>I don't know how</i>
<i>this will be assured.</i>

6
01:03:17,133 --> 01:03:19,200
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

7
01:03:21,203 --> 01:03:24,372
<i>[ON TAPE] But I do not</i>
<i>doubt that the material</i>

8
01:03:24,373 --> 01:03:27,742
<i>will be preserved.</i>

9
01:03:29,645 --> 01:03:33,148
<i>Otherwise,</i>

10
01:03:33,149 --> 01:03:34,749
<i>my life would have</i>
<i>no meaning.</i>

11
01:03:40,956 --> 01:03:41,756
[HORN HONKING]

12
01:03:45,995 --> 01:03:47,162
WOMAN [IN ENGLISH]:
Hello!

13
01:03:47,163 --> 01:03:49,330
[HORN HONKING]

14
01:03:49,331 --> 01:03:50,965
Excuse me,

15
01:03:50,966 --> 01:03:53,034
what's the best way
up to the top?

16
01:03:53,035 --> 01:03:54,602
[#]

17
01:04:01,710 --> 01:04:03,111
Is it Laura?

18
01:04:03,112 --> 01:04:05,747
She's afraid of curvy roads.

19
01:04:05,748 --> 01:04:07,916
I really don't think
you should go on.

20
01:04:07,917 --> 01:04:09,551
There's a storm coming in.

21
01:04:09,552 --> 01:04:14,622
We're used to mountain storms.
And anyway, we can't wait.

22
01:04:14,623 --> 01:04:16,024
It is.

23
01:04:20,496 --> 01:04:22,931
Our vacation will
be over in a few days.

24
01:04:22,932 --> 01:04:23,932
Maybe I can help.

25
01:04:28,137 --> 01:04:29,270
That's it.

26
01:04:31,440 --> 01:04:32,774
That's it.

27
01:04:34,243 --> 01:04:37,912
I'm Veronica.
What's your name?

28
01:04:37,913 --> 01:04:39,013
Dominic.

29
01:04:39,014 --> 01:04:41,316
With her,
you use your real name.

30
01:04:44,887 --> 01:04:45,487
VERONICA:
Thank you.

31
01:04:53,162 --> 01:04:54,562
Be careful.

32
01:04:54,563 --> 01:04:56,030
VERONICA:
Goodbye, Dominic.

33
01:04:59,001 --> 01:05:01,236
<i>DOMINIC:</i>
<i>I can only guess what happened.</i>

34
01:05:01,237 --> 01:05:03,171
<i>When the big storm broke out,</i>

35
01:05:03,172 --> 01:05:04,472
they were probably
on the road

36
01:05:04,473 --> 01:05:06,107
that runs under
the mountain wall,

37
01:05:06,108 --> 01:05:08,309
where most
of the lightning struck.

38
01:05:08,310 --> 01:05:10,745
I'm afraid they could have
been buried in a rockslide

39
01:05:10,746 --> 01:05:13,815
or a close strike of lightning
can cause a heart attack.

40
01:05:16,786 --> 01:05:17,786
Your name?

41
01:05:17,787 --> 01:05:20,021
Martin Audricourt.

42
01:05:23,225 --> 01:05:23,725
Passport, please.

43
01:05:31,267 --> 01:05:34,469
You know, I can always
go in a taxi by myself.

44
01:05:36,338 --> 01:05:38,907
If I need help, I'll call
from the first service station.

45
01:05:50,152 --> 01:05:53,321
DOMINIC: I don't think they could
have had time to reach the shelter.

46
01:05:53,322 --> 01:05:55,457
They could have taken refuge

47
01:05:55,458 --> 01:05:57,792
in one of the crevices
in the wall.

48
01:06:00,196 --> 01:06:01,763
Oh, there's their car.

49
01:06:05,134 --> 01:06:06,701
There's a woman
over here.

50
01:06:21,183 --> 01:06:22,584
She's dead.

51
01:06:32,027 --> 01:06:36,064
<i>VERONICA:</i>
<i>Om, shanti</i>

52
01:06:36,065 --> 01:06:38,333
<i>Shanti</i>

53
01:06:38,334 --> 01:06:39,667
[GASPS]

54
01:06:39,668 --> 01:06:41,035
Veronica?

55
01:06:41,036 --> 01:06:42,036
[WHIMPERING]

56
01:06:42,037 --> 01:06:44,939
What happened?
Are you all right?

57
01:06:47,076 --> 01:06:49,878
[CHANTING IN SANSKRIT]

58
01:06:49,879 --> 01:06:50,445
Sanskrit.

59
01:06:53,249 --> 01:06:54,716
How can it be?

60
01:06:58,554 --> 01:07:00,455
[CHANTING IN SANSKRIT]

61
01:07:18,240 --> 01:07:20,942
[#]

62
01:07:25,080 --> 01:07:26,347
[VERONICA YELLING]

63
01:07:26,348 --> 01:07:28,550
[DOMINIC SPEAKING
IN SANSKRIT]

64
01:07:31,420 --> 01:07:34,422
She's had a shock.
She's suffering from amnesia.

65
01:07:34,423 --> 01:07:36,858
What language is that?
What is she speaking?

66
01:07:36,859 --> 01:07:40,595
It's an Indian language,
I think.

67
01:07:40,596 --> 01:07:46,601
Her papers identify her
as Veronica Buehler, age 25.

68
01:07:46,602 --> 01:07:48,169
Occupation: school teacher.

69
01:07:48,170 --> 01:07:50,905
Living in Liestal,
Canton Bâle-Campagne.

70
01:07:50,906 --> 01:07:52,774
Excuse me.
- Please.

71
01:07:52,775 --> 01:07:55,276
You're the only one
who can calm her

72
01:07:55,277 --> 01:07:58,146
and speak her language,
Mr...?

73
01:07:58,147 --> 01:07:59,514
Audricourt.

74
01:07:59,515 --> 01:08:01,015
I'm a student of linguistics.

75
01:08:19,201 --> 01:08:21,636
[IN SANSKRIT]
Greetings.

76
01:08:21,637 --> 01:08:24,105
Greetings.

77
01:08:25,274 --> 01:08:27,575
What is your name?

78
01:08:32,248 --> 01:08:36,518
It is a pleasure
to make your acquaintance.

79
01:08:39,688 --> 01:08:42,357
My name is Rupini.

80
01:08:45,628 --> 01:08:46,694
[IN ENGLISH]
Thank you.

81
01:08:52,535 --> 01:08:54,002
Good morning.

82
01:08:57,273 --> 01:08:59,507
What can you tell us,
Mr. Audricourt?

83
01:09:12,188 --> 01:09:14,322
The young woman believes

84
01:09:14,323 --> 01:09:16,658
she is living
in northeastern India

85
01:09:16,659 --> 01:09:17,625
14 centuries ago.

86
01:09:19,728 --> 01:09:21,262
She feels
that she has spent

87
01:09:21,263 --> 01:09:25,633
several months
in a cave meditating.

88
01:09:27,570 --> 01:09:30,205
Now, this is where she was
when a big storm broke out

89
01:09:30,206 --> 01:09:34,109
and she saw lightning strike
above her on the mountain.

90
01:09:34,110 --> 01:09:39,180
Many large rocks were dislodged,
blocking the mouth of the cave.

91
01:09:42,084 --> 01:09:43,218
Is that all?

92
01:09:43,219 --> 01:09:46,154
She asserts her name
is Rupini,

93
01:09:48,023 --> 01:09:50,725
daughter of Nagabhatta,

94
01:09:50,726 --> 01:09:54,662
descended from one of the first
families to convert to Buddhism.

95
01:09:56,565 --> 01:10:02,804
She became a disciple
of the philosopher Chandrakirti,

96
01:10:02,805 --> 01:10:07,809
which is why she was in the cave
copying down his works.

97
01:10:07,810 --> 01:10:09,344
I see.

98
01:10:11,447 --> 01:10:14,449
Would you mind if I discuss this
a moment with my colleagues?

99
01:10:16,418 --> 01:10:16,951
Not at all.

100
01:10:23,058 --> 01:10:25,026
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

101
01:10:32,334 --> 01:10:32,967
[COUGHS]

102
01:10:35,905 --> 01:10:38,706
We will invite
some doctors from, uh,

103
01:10:38,707 --> 01:10:41,676
Zurich, Basel and Geneva
to come to see her.

104
01:10:43,179 --> 01:10:44,612
I...

105
01:10:44,613 --> 01:10:46,948
If I might make a suggestion?

106
01:10:46,949 --> 01:10:48,616
Yes.

107
01:10:48,617 --> 01:10:51,619
Perhaps some experts from
the Oriental Institute in Rome

108
01:10:51,620 --> 01:10:53,121
might be necessary.

109
01:10:53,122 --> 01:10:56,491
Necessary for what?

110
01:10:56,492 --> 01:11:00,295
Well, to confirm
if what she's saying is fact.

111
01:11:01,464 --> 01:11:03,064
Fact?

112
01:11:03,065 --> 01:11:04,165
Exactly.

113
01:11:10,873 --> 01:11:13,241
[SPEAKING IN ITALIAN]

114
01:11:13,242 --> 01:11:15,643
[IN ITALIAN] I present to
you Professor Giuseppe Tucci

115
01:11:15,644 --> 01:11:17,245
from the Oriental Institute
in Rome.

116
01:11:17,246 --> 01:11:19,080
I am Blasi, his assistant.

117
01:11:19,081 --> 01:11:21,950
[SPEAKING IN ITALIAN]

118
01:11:21,951 --> 01:11:24,419
[IN ENGLISH] Professor
Tucci, it's an honor.

119
01:11:32,928 --> 01:11:36,498
Before we begin,
who wrote the telegram

120
01:11:36,499 --> 01:11:38,333
that included
some of the particulars?

121
01:11:38,334 --> 01:11:40,468
I did, professor.

122
01:11:40,469 --> 01:11:42,003
You're a Sanskritist?

123
01:11:42,004 --> 01:11:44,639
Not exactly. Excuse me.

124
01:11:44,640 --> 01:11:46,975
Uh, but I have an interest
in Oriental studies.

125
01:11:46,976 --> 01:11:49,778
I came only because
of your report.

126
01:11:49,779 --> 01:11:51,146
Thank you.

127
01:11:51,147 --> 01:11:53,581
[IN ITALIAN]
You did well.

128
01:12:00,890 --> 01:12:03,057
[IN SANSKRIT]
Well-being, your ladyship.

129
01:12:03,058 --> 01:12:04,225
Well-being, your ladyship.

130
01:12:06,562 --> 01:12:08,930
Welcome to both of you.

131
01:12:11,400 --> 01:12:13,968
Where am I?

132
01:12:13,969 --> 01:12:17,939
Why doesn't anybody
understand me?

133
01:12:20,476 --> 01:12:28,249
As in dreams, the mind presents
the appearance of duality.

134
01:12:28,250 --> 01:12:31,252
[IN ENGLISH] We've had some of her
remarks translated into English.

135
01:12:33,222 --> 01:12:37,559
The young woman's knowledge
of Madhyamika philosophy

136
01:12:37,560 --> 01:12:40,995
and her master, Chandrakirti,
is convincing.

137
01:12:42,498 --> 01:12:44,966
The discussion only became
delicate whenever Rupini

138
01:12:44,967 --> 01:12:50,538
asked what had happened to her,
where she was

139
01:12:50,539 --> 01:12:52,607
and why no one understood her.

140
01:12:52,608 --> 01:12:54,542
What did you tell her,
professor?

141
01:12:54,543 --> 01:12:56,711
[IN ITALIAN] I always
begin by reminding of maya.

142
01:12:56,712 --> 01:12:58,913
[CHUCKLES]
The cosmic illusion.

143
01:12:58,914 --> 01:13:01,416
TUCCI:
The great witch.

144
01:13:01,417 --> 01:13:03,618
[IN ENGLISH] Actually it's
not a dream, I told her,

145
01:13:03,619 --> 01:13:04,786
but it takes part

146
01:13:04,787 --> 01:13:07,355
in the illusory nature
of dreaming,

147
01:13:07,356 --> 01:13:12,627
because it is the future,
therefore, of time.

148
01:13:12,628 --> 01:13:16,598
Now, time is
par excellence unreal.

149
01:13:16,599 --> 01:13:18,800
I don't believe
I convinced her.

150
01:13:18,801 --> 01:13:20,001
But fortunately, she's, uh,

151
01:13:20,002 --> 01:13:21,936
enthusiastic about logic
and dialectics,

152
01:13:21,937 --> 01:13:23,905
and that's mainly
what we discussed.

153
01:13:23,906 --> 01:13:25,373
MAN [IN ITALIAN]:
Uh, professor,

154
01:13:25,374 --> 01:13:29,177
could all this possibly be...?

155
01:13:29,178 --> 01:13:31,746
How shall I say?

156
01:13:31,747 --> 01:13:33,248
[IN ENGLISH]
Fact?

157
01:13:33,249 --> 01:13:35,350
"Fact"?

158
01:13:37,586 --> 01:13:39,120
Mmm.

159
01:13:39,121 --> 01:13:40,989
I would suggest
a journey to India,

160
01:13:40,990 --> 01:13:43,725
more precisely to the province
of Uttar Pradesh,

161
01:13:43,726 --> 01:13:47,896
to the caves where Rupini
claims to have meditated.

162
01:13:47,897 --> 01:13:51,232
I should think
the Oriental Institute of Rome,

163
01:13:51,233 --> 01:13:55,069
of which I am president,
would sponsor the expedition.

164
01:13:55,070 --> 01:13:56,171
And, young man,

165
01:13:56,172 --> 01:13:58,973
I think you should
accompany us to India.

166
01:13:58,974 --> 01:14:00,708
I'd be delighted,
professor.

167
01:14:00,709 --> 01:14:02,277
[SPEAKS IN ITALIAN]

168
01:14:02,278 --> 01:14:04,913
It's been understood she will
be put into a deep sleep

169
01:14:04,914 --> 01:14:06,214
before leaving the clinic

170
01:14:06,215 --> 01:14:07,816
and will continue
to sleep

171
01:14:07,817 --> 01:14:10,718
until we reach the vicinity
of the caves.

172
01:14:11,821 --> 01:14:13,721
[#]

173
01:14:27,269 --> 01:14:28,369
[INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER]

174
01:14:42,318 --> 01:14:43,418
[TIRES SCREECH]

175
01:14:53,863 --> 01:14:55,363
[CHATTERING
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

176
01:14:55,364 --> 01:14:56,931
MAN:
Start rolling. Rolling!

177
01:14:56,932 --> 01:14:58,233
Tucci! Tucci, look here!

178
01:14:58,234 --> 01:14:59,300
[MAN SPEAKS
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

179
01:15:19,755 --> 01:15:21,256
[#]

180
01:15:36,439 --> 01:15:38,773
We are very close
to the frontier of Nepal.

181
01:15:38,774 --> 01:15:41,042
According to Rupini's account,

182
01:15:41,043 --> 01:15:43,511
this is where we'll find the
cave where she would meditate.

183
01:15:54,790 --> 01:15:57,659
[CAMERA WHIRRING]

184
01:16:00,930 --> 01:16:03,031
[GOATS BLEATING]

185
01:16:08,237 --> 01:16:11,005
We are very fortunate in having
a pandit from Gorakhpur

186
01:16:11,006 --> 01:16:13,374
familiar with
the Madhyamika philosophy.

187
01:16:13,375 --> 01:16:15,243
He'll be at her side
when she awakens.

188
01:16:15,244 --> 01:16:18,213
[CAMERA WHIRRING]

189
01:16:22,485 --> 01:16:24,185
[SPEAKING IN SANSKRIT]

190
01:16:27,289 --> 01:16:28,857
Everyone,
hide themselves.

191
01:16:28,858 --> 01:16:30,191
[SPEAKS IN ITALIAN]

192
01:16:31,660 --> 01:16:32,761
[SPEAKS IN ITALIAN]

193
01:16:32,762 --> 01:16:35,530
[CAMERA WHIRRING]

194
01:16:45,708 --> 01:16:48,076
[IN SANSKRIT]
No form,

195
01:16:48,077 --> 01:16:50,712
no feeling,

196
01:16:50,713 --> 01:16:51,946
no thought,

197
01:16:51,947 --> 01:16:54,549
no choice,

198
01:16:56,252 --> 01:16:58,052
no consciousness.

199
01:17:02,992 --> 01:17:05,493
Gone, gone,

200
01:17:05,494 --> 01:17:08,196
gone beyond,
completely gone.

201
01:17:09,465 --> 01:17:11,533
Enlightenment.

202
01:17:11,534 --> 01:17:12,867
So be it.

203
01:17:13,903 --> 01:17:14,936
Welcome.

204
01:17:26,248 --> 01:17:30,018
Why did it take you so long?

205
01:17:30,019 --> 01:17:32,487
I was already here.

206
01:17:40,463 --> 01:17:42,397
[BELLS JINGLING]
[GOATS BLEATING]

207
01:17:55,277 --> 01:17:56,778
[#]

208
01:17:59,215 --> 01:18:03,184
I know this place.

209
01:18:23,906 --> 01:18:25,874
[IN ENGLISH]
Stay back. Hide yourself.

210
01:18:33,482 --> 01:18:34,949
[IN SANSKRIT]
Over here!

211
01:18:55,037 --> 01:18:56,371
Ah!

212
01:18:56,372 --> 01:18:58,473
[YELLS]

213
01:18:58,474 --> 01:19:00,008
[IN ENGLISH]
Oh, God.

214
01:19:00,009 --> 01:19:01,042
Are you all right?

215
01:19:11,220 --> 01:19:13,054
DOMINIC:
Just be still. Lay still.

216
01:19:14,390 --> 01:19:15,790
Just rest.

217
01:19:15,791 --> 01:19:17,091
Veronica.

218
01:19:18,727 --> 01:19:20,662
TUCCI [IN ITALIAN]:
She recognized it.

219
01:19:20,663 --> 01:19:23,098
This is the cave!

220
01:19:23,099 --> 01:19:24,632
But the entrance is blocked.

221
01:19:24,633 --> 01:19:26,334
[CAMERA WHIRRING]

222
01:19:44,386 --> 01:19:46,121
[#]

223
01:19:52,161 --> 01:19:54,195
[SPEAKING IN SANSKRIT]

224
01:20:43,512 --> 01:20:47,515
[IN ENGLISH] I don't think
you'll be needing me for a while.

225
01:20:58,427 --> 01:20:59,894
[CROWD CHATTERING]

226
01:21:03,599 --> 01:21:04,599
[BIRDS SQUAWKING]

227
01:21:11,941 --> 01:21:13,675
WOMAN:
She is awake,

228
01:21:13,676 --> 01:21:15,910
but she has not
opened her eyes.

229
01:21:23,686 --> 01:21:25,320
[IN SANSKRIT]
Greetings.

230
01:21:29,859 --> 01:21:33,328
How are you feeling, Rupini?

231
01:21:40,136 --> 01:21:44,239
[IN ENGLISH] Didn't we--? Didn't
we ask directions of you today?

232
01:21:47,176 --> 01:21:49,110
<i>My name is Veronica Buehler,</i>

233
01:21:49,111 --> 01:21:51,780
<i>and I speak three languages:</i>

234
01:21:51,781 --> 01:21:54,349
<i>German, French and English.</i>

235
01:21:54,350 --> 01:21:57,519
<i>TUCCI: Have you ever tried to</i>
<i>learn any Oriental language?</i>

236
01:21:57,520 --> 01:21:58,686
<i>Never.</i>

237
01:21:58,687 --> 01:22:01,156
<i>TUCCI:</i>
<i>Or have you ever read anything</i>

238
01:22:01,157 --> 01:22:03,124
<i>about India</i>
<i>or Indian culture?</i>

239
01:22:03,125 --> 01:22:04,926
<i>Some popular books.</i>

240
01:22:04,927 --> 01:22:06,094
<i>TUCCI:</i>
<i>Like?</i>

241
01:22:06,095 --> 01:22:09,030
<i>Heh. Rudyard Kipling,</i>
<i>I think?</i>

242
01:22:09,031 --> 01:22:10,331
The Jungle Book.

243
01:22:10,332 --> 01:22:11,900
<i>[CROWD LAUGHS]</i>
<i>Have you ever heard</i>

244
01:22:11,901 --> 01:22:14,235
<i>the name Rupini?</i>

245
01:22:14,236 --> 01:22:15,937
<i>No.</i>

246
01:22:15,938 --> 01:22:18,006
<i>TUCCI:</i>
<i>In an earlier existence,</i>

247
01:22:18,007 --> 01:22:20,675
<i>Veronica Buehler</i>
<i>had been Rupini.</i>

248
01:22:20,676 --> 01:22:24,979
<i>I would say, for the vast</i>
<i>majority of the Orientalists,</i>

249
01:22:24,980 --> 01:22:30,285
<i>a clear example of</i>
<i>the transmigration of the soul.</i>

250
01:22:30,286 --> 01:22:32,454
<i>And, young man, your opinion?</i>

251
01:22:32,455 --> 01:22:34,756
<i>As a neophyte Orientalist,</i>

252
01:22:34,757 --> 01:22:37,125
<i>I can only cite some classical</i>
<i>Indian conceptions,</i>

253
01:22:37,126 --> 01:22:40,428
<i>from Upanishads</i>
<i>to Gautama Buddha.</i>

254
01:22:40,429 --> 01:22:43,431
<i>BLASI: Excuse me. It is</i>
<i>precisely in the Upanishads</i>

255
01:22:43,432 --> 01:22:46,568
<i>in the Brhadaranyaka</i>
<i>and Chandogya Upanishads</i>

256
01:22:46,569 --> 01:22:49,904
<i>that one can find this belief</i>
<i>for the first time.</i>

257
01:22:49,905 --> 01:22:51,773
<i>This is karma, isn't it?</i>

258
01:22:51,774 --> 01:22:53,741
VERONICA:
But it's hard for me to believe

259
01:22:53,742 --> 01:22:55,376
that I ever existed before.

260
01:22:55,377 --> 01:22:57,312
How did you say?

261
01:22:57,313 --> 01:22:58,947
Metempsychosis.

262
01:22:58,948 --> 01:23:01,416
Metempsychosis.
- Mm-hm.

263
01:23:01,417 --> 01:23:03,384
That absolutely
doesn't make sense to me.

264
01:23:05,688 --> 01:23:07,188
Maybe...

265
01:23:07,189 --> 01:23:08,756
What?

266
01:23:08,757 --> 01:23:11,693
Maybe I was possessed
by an evil spirit.

267
01:23:11,694 --> 01:23:13,695
Well...

268
01:23:13,696 --> 01:23:15,296
VERONICA:
They never leave us alone.

269
01:23:15,297 --> 01:23:18,233
[CAMERA CLICKS]
It's all so confusing.

270
01:23:18,234 --> 01:23:20,335
I'm afraid
I'm going crazy.

271
01:23:20,336 --> 01:23:22,137
[CAMERA CLICKING]

272
01:23:24,473 --> 01:23:25,940
[CROWD CHATTERING]

273
01:23:30,813 --> 01:23:33,648
Hello, Miss Veronica,
just an interview.

274
01:23:33,649 --> 01:23:36,017
That's enough. Let's go.

275
01:23:36,018 --> 01:23:37,318
DOMINIC:
Taxi!

276
01:23:42,124 --> 01:23:43,892
Just drive, drive anywhere.

277
01:23:43,893 --> 01:23:45,126
[DOMINIC & VERONICA LAUGH]

278
01:24:20,396 --> 01:24:23,865
I-- I think
we should get away. I...

279
01:24:25,601 --> 01:24:28,503
I think we should go somewhere.
We should be alone.

280
01:24:28,504 --> 01:24:30,305
We should go to, uh,
somewhere beautiful,

281
01:24:30,306 --> 01:24:31,172
a Mediterranean island.

282
01:24:33,409 --> 01:24:36,411
Dominic, that would make me
very, very happy.

283
01:24:36,412 --> 01:24:38,346
[#]

284
01:24:49,492 --> 01:24:51,459
[BIRDS CAWING]

285
01:25:00,669 --> 01:25:02,170
[CRICKET CHIRPING]

286
01:25:24,794 --> 01:25:27,095
[BIRD SQUAWKING]

287
01:25:27,096 --> 01:25:29,764
VERONICA:
Look, that bird.

288
01:25:29,765 --> 01:25:32,200
What kind of birds
do they have in Malta?

289
01:25:32,201 --> 01:25:33,802
DOMINIC:
That's a Maltese falcon.

290
01:25:33,803 --> 01:25:34,602
[VERONICA CHUCKLES]

291
01:25:53,522 --> 01:25:55,223
[IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]
Welcome.

292
01:25:55,224 --> 01:25:57,459
[IN ENGLISH]
Thank you.

293
01:26:03,566 --> 01:26:05,300
No, that's fine.
Thank you.

294
01:26:05,301 --> 01:26:06,668
Thank you.

295
01:26:12,775 --> 01:26:14,275
Thanks very much.

296
01:26:18,247 --> 01:26:20,014
Finally alone.

297
01:26:25,888 --> 01:26:28,623
Dominic,
it's beautiful here.

298
01:26:28,624 --> 01:26:30,024
Yes, it is.

299
01:26:40,269 --> 01:26:43,171
When I first opened my eyes
and saw you...

300
01:26:46,675 --> 01:26:49,911
I confess I was thinking,

301
01:26:49,912 --> 01:26:54,549
if I were three
or four years older and...

302
01:26:57,720 --> 01:26:59,554
if he were
to ask me to marry him...

303
01:27:03,893 --> 01:27:05,560
I would say yes.

304
01:27:06,562 --> 01:27:09,197
[#]

305
01:27:17,406 --> 01:27:18,640
Veronica.

306
01:27:34,390 --> 01:27:36,157
DOMINIC:
My love.

307
01:27:36,158 --> 01:27:38,259
Is it true?

308
01:27:47,470 --> 01:27:48,736
Yes.

309
01:27:58,314 --> 01:28:00,115
I've always loved you.

310
01:28:29,044 --> 01:28:29,711
Veronica?

311
01:28:42,458 --> 01:28:44,759
[MUTTERS]

312
01:28:44,760 --> 01:28:47,228
[CLEARS THROAT]

313
01:28:47,229 --> 01:28:51,733
[SPEAKING IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

314
01:29:17,426 --> 01:29:18,460
Do you understand it?

315
01:29:20,629 --> 01:29:22,764
I don't know this language.

316
01:29:24,834 --> 01:29:28,636
Ancient... Beyond...

317
01:29:28,637 --> 01:29:30,138
Why else did you have
to know her?

318
01:29:35,244 --> 01:29:39,147
[CONTINUES
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

319
01:29:52,128 --> 01:29:54,095
[PANTING]

320
01:29:55,698 --> 01:29:56,598
[GROANING]

321
01:30:02,138 --> 01:30:03,605
[CLEARS THROAT]

322
01:30:05,875 --> 01:30:06,941
[CLEARS THROAT]

323
01:30:08,477 --> 01:30:12,714
[SCREAMS]

324
01:30:15,317 --> 01:30:17,552
[#]

325
01:30:20,356 --> 01:30:22,123
[PANTING]

326
01:30:29,265 --> 01:30:30,498
Veronica?

327
01:30:35,504 --> 01:30:36,504
Veronica...

328
01:30:36,505 --> 01:30:37,005
[HISSING]

329
01:30:44,447 --> 01:30:45,447
[GRUNTS]

330
01:30:52,755 --> 01:30:53,888
It's all right.

331
01:30:53,889 --> 01:30:55,957
That's all right.
It's all right.

332
01:30:55,958 --> 01:30:58,660
I've got you.
I've got you.

333
01:30:58,661 --> 01:31:00,929
I've got you, darling.
[SNIFFLES]

334
01:31:00,930 --> 01:31:03,698
I've got you, Laura.

335
01:31:03,699 --> 01:31:06,634
[WHIMPERS]
It's all right.

336
01:31:06,635 --> 01:31:08,536
I've got you.

337
01:31:08,537 --> 01:31:11,539
I've got you, darling.
I've got you, Laura.

338
01:31:15,044 --> 01:31:17,445
I love you, darling.

339
01:31:17,446 --> 01:31:19,047
I love you.

340
01:31:28,524 --> 01:31:32,026
<i>[VERONICA SPEAKING</i>
<i>IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]</i>

341
01:31:44,807 --> 01:31:47,909
[TAPE REWINDING]

342
01:31:50,946 --> 01:31:53,982
<i>[VERONICA SPEAKING</i>
<i>IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]</i>

343
01:32:10,699 --> 01:32:11,499
[TAPE CLICKS OFF]

344
01:32:23,946 --> 01:32:25,713
Was that Rupini's voice?

345
01:32:25,714 --> 01:32:28,082
Mm-hm. Yes.

346
01:32:28,083 --> 01:32:30,251
She's moving back in time

347
01:32:30,252 --> 01:32:33,955
from Sanskrit
to earlier languages.

348
01:32:33,956 --> 01:32:35,356
That was Egyptian.

349
01:32:41,597 --> 01:32:44,299
Perhaps you'll take us back
to a time before history.

350
01:32:46,502 --> 01:32:48,636
The origins of language,

351
01:32:48,637 --> 01:32:52,340
which is where I've always
wanted to go, but I never could.

352
01:32:52,341 --> 01:32:54,909
But it's helping me
finish my work.

353
01:32:54,910 --> 01:32:55,844
Good.

354
01:32:57,513 --> 01:32:59,814
Good. I want to help you.

355
01:32:59,815 --> 01:33:00,582
You know, I'm...

356
01:33:03,018 --> 01:33:06,721
I'm 88 years old, really.

357
01:33:06,722 --> 01:33:08,323
[#]

358
01:33:08,324 --> 01:33:09,824
[CHUCKLES]

359
01:33:12,194 --> 01:33:15,163
If I added up all the years
Rupini lived,

360
01:33:15,164 --> 01:33:16,030
I'd be older than you.

361
01:33:18,067 --> 01:33:18,833
Well, then let's go dancing.

362
01:33:24,640 --> 01:33:26,141
[FIREWORKS POPPING]

363
01:33:30,012 --> 01:33:31,312
[LAUGHTER]

364
01:33:37,286 --> 01:33:39,420
[CROWD CHATTERING]

365
01:33:39,421 --> 01:33:41,356
[BAND PLAYING MELLOW MUSIC]

366
01:33:50,900 --> 01:33:51,900
DOMINIC:
Thank you.

367
01:34:06,382 --> 01:34:07,916
[LAUGHING]

368
01:34:11,353 --> 01:34:12,854
I don't think
we'll be recognized,

369
01:34:12,855 --> 01:34:15,356
even with our pictures
in all those magazines.

370
01:34:15,357 --> 01:34:19,427
Well, our pictures
are still appearing.

371
01:34:19,428 --> 01:34:20,562
Let me see.

372
01:34:34,243 --> 01:34:36,044
[#]

373
01:34:39,648 --> 01:34:40,615
What's the matter?

374
01:34:48,524 --> 01:34:51,459
I feel tired all the time,

375
01:34:51,460 --> 01:34:54,596
and I don't understand why.

376
01:34:54,597 --> 01:34:59,334
Something is happening
inside me. I can feel it.

377
01:34:59,335 --> 01:35:00,869
THE DOUBLE:
And she's right.

378
01:35:00,870 --> 01:35:03,838
The paramediumistic ecstasies
have exhausted her.

379
01:35:07,376 --> 01:35:10,011
[CORK POPS]

380
01:35:10,012 --> 01:35:11,513
MAN:
Champagne?

381
01:35:17,486 --> 01:35:18,820
[MAN SPEAKS
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

382
01:35:53,456 --> 01:35:55,390
[#]

383
01:36:01,831 --> 01:36:03,498
[CLOCK TICKING]

384
01:36:49,245 --> 01:36:50,578
Veronica?

385
01:36:58,888 --> 01:37:00,522
Veronica!

386
01:37:11,600 --> 01:37:13,601
[SHOUTS
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

387
01:37:20,776 --> 01:37:24,179
No! Veronica, don't!

388
01:37:26,215 --> 01:37:27,649
Veronica!

389
01:37:28,884 --> 01:37:29,584
I was so worried!

390
01:37:31,654 --> 01:37:33,087
What is it?

391
01:37:33,088 --> 01:37:34,956
It was a dream.

392
01:37:34,957 --> 01:37:38,059
A bad dream.

393
01:37:38,060 --> 01:37:40,495
What was--? What was it?

394
01:37:43,065 --> 01:37:46,334
I was somewhere beside a river,
and someone,

395
01:37:46,335 --> 01:37:48,636
a stranger with a head
like a dog,

396
01:37:48,637 --> 01:37:50,305
was coming toward me.

397
01:37:50,306 --> 01:37:53,041
And in his hand, he--
He had...

398
01:37:55,578 --> 01:37:57,278
Explain it to me!

399
01:37:57,279 --> 01:38:00,048
I want to know
what Rupini knows.

400
01:38:00,049 --> 01:38:03,718
She knows things
that we don't understand yet.

401
01:38:03,719 --> 01:38:05,687
No. Let me--

402
01:38:05,688 --> 01:38:07,922
No, no!

403
01:38:07,923 --> 01:38:09,290
Don't ever leave me.

404
01:38:09,291 --> 01:38:10,592
I'll never leave you.

405
01:38:10,593 --> 01:38:12,694
Don't ever leave me.
I'll never leave you.

406
01:38:12,695 --> 01:38:15,163
Don't ever leave me.

407
01:38:15,164 --> 01:38:16,231
I'll never leave you.

408
01:38:23,939 --> 01:38:25,240
[MOANING SOFTLY]

409
01:38:38,087 --> 01:38:40,021
[#]

410
01:38:50,299 --> 01:38:52,200
[GROWLING]

411
01:39:02,278 --> 01:39:04,045
Veronica.
[MOANS]

412
01:39:12,221 --> 01:39:16,057
The stranger in your dream
was probably Shiva.

413
01:39:18,994 --> 01:39:21,529
And in his hand, a skull.

414
01:39:23,666 --> 01:39:28,369
For Shiva is both creator
and destroyer combined.

415
01:39:35,544 --> 01:39:37,045
[#]

416
01:40:11,280 --> 01:40:12,280
[SIGHS]

417
01:40:23,259 --> 01:40:24,259
Dominic?

418
01:40:24,260 --> 01:40:25,760
There's someone
who looks like you

419
01:40:25,761 --> 01:40:27,862
spying on us.

420
01:40:27,863 --> 01:40:29,164
I didn't notice anyone.

421
01:40:29,165 --> 01:40:30,899
By the gate.

422
01:40:30,900 --> 01:40:31,933
Come and look.

423
01:40:42,278 --> 01:40:43,144
There's no one there.

424
01:40:52,421 --> 01:40:54,355
Maybe I was mistaken.

425
01:40:56,826 --> 01:40:59,828
You've been in the sun too long.
Let's go inside.

426
01:41:22,751 --> 01:41:26,588
<i>DOMINIC:</i>
<i>I'm 88 years old, really.</i>

427
01:41:31,393 --> 01:41:33,094
[INSECTS BUZZING]

428
01:41:33,095 --> 01:41:34,362
[PANTING]

429
01:41:52,114 --> 01:41:53,515
[MOANS]

430
01:42:12,935 --> 01:42:15,570
THE DOUBLE: She's in a
hyper-suggestive state.

431
01:42:17,373 --> 01:42:18,573
Tell her you love her.

432
01:42:20,910 --> 01:42:22,377
Tell her that you've
always loved her.

433
01:42:25,881 --> 01:42:27,282
I love you.

434
01:42:29,919 --> 01:42:31,853
I've always loved you.

435
01:42:37,326 --> 01:42:39,561
[SPEAKING
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

436
01:42:44,133 --> 01:42:45,333
That's Sumerian.

437
01:42:46,535 --> 01:42:49,170
[SPEAKING
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

438
01:42:55,277 --> 01:42:56,778
No, it's Babylonian.

439
01:42:56,779 --> 01:42:59,681
[SPEAKING
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

440
01:43:07,890 --> 01:43:09,624
[VERONICA SPEAKING
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

441
01:43:12,595 --> 01:43:15,196
<i>DOMINIC:</i>
<i>After Egyptian and Babylonian,</i>

442
01:43:15,197 --> 01:43:17,999
there followed probably
a sample of proto-Elamite

443
01:43:18,000 --> 01:43:20,335
and one of Sumerian.

444
01:43:20,336 --> 01:43:23,705
She is descending
deeper and deeper

445
01:43:23,706 --> 01:43:25,039
into the past.

446
01:43:25,040 --> 01:43:27,342
But how far back will she go?

447
01:43:27,343 --> 01:43:30,578
Your life's work will
finally have what was missing.

448
01:43:33,015 --> 01:43:35,049
<i>DOMINIC:</i>
<i>Every night for two weeks,</i>

449
01:43:35,050 --> 01:43:38,620
<i>Veronica went</i>
<i>further back in time.</i>

450
01:43:38,621 --> 01:43:40,421
<i>Through unknown languages...</i>

451
01:43:45,060 --> 01:43:46,995
<i>unwritten history.</i>

452
01:43:58,107 --> 01:44:00,475
<i>Getting closer...</i>

453
01:44:00,476 --> 01:44:02,010
<i>and closer...</i>

454
01:44:02,011 --> 01:44:06,347
to the inarticulate moment...

455
01:44:06,348 --> 01:44:08,049
of the beginning.

456
01:44:08,050 --> 01:44:09,684
[#]

457
01:44:18,260 --> 01:44:20,695
<i>DOMINIC:</i>
<i>But at what cost?</i>

458
01:44:22,998 --> 01:44:24,265
<i>MAN:</i>
<i>Madam is not suffering</i>

459
01:44:24,266 --> 01:44:26,367
from anything,
anything at all.

460
01:44:26,368 --> 01:44:27,669
Are you sure, doctor?

461
01:44:27,670 --> 01:44:30,605
Yes. I've prescribed
a series of shots

462
01:44:30,606 --> 01:44:33,274
with vitamins and minerals.

463
01:44:33,275 --> 01:44:35,310
Perhaps it's...

464
01:44:35,311 --> 01:44:37,946
the nervous condition

465
01:44:37,947 --> 01:44:40,482
that precedes menopause

466
01:44:40,483 --> 01:44:42,851
in certain women.

467
01:44:42,852 --> 01:44:46,454
Well, just how old do you
take her to be, doctor?

468
01:44:46,455 --> 01:44:48,756
Late 40s, more or less.

469
01:44:50,426 --> 01:44:51,526
She's 25.

470
01:45:12,081 --> 01:45:13,148
Where have all
the mirrors gone?

471
01:45:21,590 --> 01:45:23,458
Bring one to me.

472
01:45:25,127 --> 01:45:27,429
Veronica, you're not well.

473
01:45:28,731 --> 01:45:31,399
Bring a mirror to me,
Dominic, please.

474
01:45:34,904 --> 01:45:35,703
Maybe that one.

475
01:45:38,874 --> 01:45:40,575
[#]

476
01:46:15,678 --> 01:46:17,112
[SIGHS]

477
01:46:23,552 --> 01:46:24,953
[WHIMPERS]

478
01:46:28,257 --> 01:46:29,691
[VERONICA SOBS]

479
01:46:34,029 --> 01:46:35,096
[SOBBING]

480
01:46:39,401 --> 01:46:40,835
[SNIFFLES]

481
01:46:45,040 --> 01:46:46,341
[WHIMPERING]

482
01:46:56,218 --> 01:47:00,288
I should have understood this
from the beginning.

483
01:47:00,289 --> 01:47:01,790
One more regression,

484
01:47:01,791 --> 01:47:03,958
she'll reach
the protolanguage.

485
01:47:03,959 --> 01:47:06,194
Your life's work
will be complete.

486
01:47:08,731 --> 01:47:10,198
You know I'm right.

487
01:47:29,251 --> 01:47:30,285
VERONICA:
Dominic?

488
01:47:33,222 --> 01:47:34,522
Dominic?

489
01:47:36,192 --> 01:47:37,392
[#]

490
01:47:41,664 --> 01:47:42,931
Look.

491
01:47:49,138 --> 01:47:50,738
Come sit with me.

492
01:47:53,876 --> 01:47:54,576
Come sit with me.

493
01:48:01,016 --> 01:48:02,283
Veronica.

494
01:48:02,284 --> 01:48:04,252
Veronica, I'm to blame for this.
No, it's me.

495
01:48:04,253 --> 01:48:06,254
Listen to me. Listen to me
and don't interrupt.

496
01:48:06,255 --> 01:48:08,857
Please, listen.
[SOBS]

497
01:48:08,858 --> 01:48:09,958
Listen to me.

498
01:48:11,260 --> 01:48:12,694
If I continue to live with you,

499
01:48:12,695 --> 01:48:14,362
by autumn
you will have perished.

500
01:48:14,363 --> 01:48:15,897
I can't tell you more.

501
01:48:15,898 --> 01:48:18,299
But I assure you,

502
01:48:18,300 --> 01:48:21,269
in reality, you haven't aged.

503
01:48:21,270 --> 01:48:22,937
The moment I disappear
from your life,

504
01:48:22,938 --> 01:48:24,773
your youth and your beauty
will return.

505
01:48:24,774 --> 01:48:28,843
Don't leave me, Dominic.
Please, don't leave me.

506
01:48:28,844 --> 01:48:31,012
I was doomed to lose everything
that I love.

507
01:48:31,013 --> 01:48:33,615
But I'd rather lose you young
and beautiful, the way you were,

508
01:48:33,616 --> 01:48:37,752
the way you will be again
without me,

509
01:48:37,753 --> 01:48:39,420
than to watch you perish
in my arms.

510
01:48:39,421 --> 01:48:43,391
You promised me
you would never leave me.

511
01:48:43,392 --> 01:48:47,762
I am going to leave you.

512
01:48:47,763 --> 01:48:51,766
If you leave me,
I will die without you.

513
01:48:51,767 --> 01:48:53,234
If in a few months,

514
01:48:53,235 --> 01:48:56,204
you don't find yourself
as you were last autumn,

515
01:48:56,205 --> 01:48:57,472
I'll come back.

516
01:48:57,473 --> 01:49:00,141
The minute I receive
your telegram, I'll come back.

517
01:49:00,142 --> 01:49:02,644
Three or four months,
just wait--

518
01:49:08,217 --> 01:49:09,150
Somewhere...

519
01:49:11,887 --> 01:49:13,655
far away from me.

520
01:49:17,760 --> 01:49:20,962
Don't leave me.
Please. Please.

521
01:49:22,598 --> 01:49:24,466
[#]

522
01:49:41,117 --> 01:49:42,317
[SOBBING]

523
01:49:52,995 --> 01:49:54,129
[SOBS, SNIFFLES]

524
01:49:54,130 --> 01:49:56,297
Dominic.

525
01:49:56,298 --> 01:49:57,198
Dominic.

